## Modified Keys

You get the following symbols by holding Shift + another key.

### `~` tilde

This symbol is used as a shortcut for your home directory in unix-like systems, and for many other purposes


::: {.cell .column-screen-inset-shaded .caption-margin}
::: {.cell-output-display}
![tilde on the tenkeyless keyboard](index_files/figure-html/unnamed-chunk-11-1.png){width=150%}
:::
:::



::: {.cell .column-screen-inset-shaded .caption-margin}
::: {.cell-output-display}
![tilde on the mac keyboard](index_files/figure-html/unnamed-chunk-12-1.png){width=150%}
:::
:::


### `^` caret

This symbol is *sometimes* used to indicate the Control key on a Mac keyboard, but usually it's the caret.


::: {.cell .column-screen-inset-shaded .caption-margin}
::: {.cell-output-display}
![caret on the tenkeyless keyboard](index_files/figure-html/unnamed-chunk-13-1.png){width=150%}
:::
:::



::: {.cell .column-screen-inset-shaded .caption-margin}
::: {.cell-output-display}
![caret on the mac keyboard](index_files/figure-html/unnamed-chunk-14-1.png){width=150%}
:::
:::


### `_` underscore

Underscores are often used in file and variable names.


::: {.cell .column-screen-inset-shaded .caption-margin}
::: {.cell-output-display}
![underscore on the tenkeyless keyboard](index_files/figure-html/unnamed-chunk-15-1.png){width=150%}
:::
:::



::: {.cell .column-screen-inset-shaded .caption-margin}
::: {.cell-output-display}
![underscore on the mac keyboard](index_files/figure-html/unnamed-chunk-16-1.png){width=150%}
:::
:::


### `{` and `}` curly brackets

A lot like the square brackets, these serve a number of different uses. And again, when you have an open backet `{` you'll want to make sure you close it `}`.


::: {.cell .column-screen-inset-shaded .caption-margin}
::: {.cell-output-display}
![curly brackets on the tenkeyless keyboard](index_files/figure-html/unnamed-chunk-17-1.png){width=150%}
:::
:::



::: {.cell .column-screen-inset-shaded .caption-margin}
::: {.cell-output-display}
![curly brackets on the mac keyboard](index_files/figure-html/unnamed-chunk-18-1.png){width=150%}
:::
:::


### `|` pipe *or* bar

This vertical line often means "or" in programming languages.


::: {.cell .column-screen-inset-shaded .caption-margin}
::: {.cell-output-display}
![bar location on the tenkeyless keyboard](index_files/figure-html/unnamed-chunk-19-1.png){width=150%}
:::
:::



::: {.cell .column-screen-inset-shaded .caption-margin}
::: {.cell-output-display}
![bar brackets on the mac keyboard](index_files/figure-html/unnamed-chunk-20-1.png){width=150%}
:::
:::


### `<` and `>` less than & greater than *or* angle brackets

Sometimes the symbols `<` and `>` are used for their mathematical meaning of "less than" and "greater than." Other times they're used as brackets, a lot like the square or curly brackets.


::: {.cell .column-screen-inset-shaded .caption-margin}
::: {.cell-output-display}
![angle bracket location on the tenkeyless keyboard](index_files/figure-html/unnamed-chunk-21-1.png){width=150%}
:::
:::



::: {.cell .column-screen-inset-shaded .caption-margin}
::: {.cell-output-display}
![angle bracket location on the tenkeyless keyboard](index_files/figure-html/unnamed-chunk-22-1.png){width=150%}
:::
:::


## Modifier Combos

Sometimes you'll see key combinations suggested to help you use the command line and other programming languages. For example, the key combo "Control+C" or "Ctrl+C" will end whatever process is running in a Unix-like system. What this notation means is that you should press the `Control` key, and while continuing to hold it, press the `C` key.


::: {.cell .column-screen-inset-shaded .caption-margin}
::: {.cell-output-display}
![Ctrl+C location on the tenkeyless keyboard](index_files/figure-html/unnamed-chunk-23-1.png){width=150%}
:::
:::



::: {.cell .column-screen-inset-shaded .caption-margin}
::: {.cell-output-display}
![Ctrl+C location on the tenkeyless keyboard](index_files/figure-html/unnamed-chunk-24-1.png){width=150%}
:::
:::


If you ever see more than two keys included in a key combination, assume they need to be pressed and held in the order they appear.
